# Document-as-Code Constitution

This project treats documentation as software: structured, versioned, validated,
indexed, traceable. The system must remain rebuildable from documentation alone,
even if all code is discarded.

## Non-negotiables

- Update documentation BEFORE or WITH any change to behavior, architecture, API
  contracts, permissions, security, data handling, or deployment assumptions.
- Keep confirmed requirements separate from pending questions. Never promote an
  assumption, recommendation, or common pattern into a confirmed requirement.
- Source-of-truth order on conflict: latest explicit user confirmation >
  `docs/requirements/requirements-plan.md` > `docs/product/PRD.md` >
  `docs/domain/domain-model.md` > `docs/security/permission-matrix.md` > ADRs.
  Never silently pick a side; surface the conflict and confirm.
- Durable decisions are ADRs. Do NOT edit accepted ADR decisions to reflect
  implementation progress — ADR status records a decision, not task completion.
- Completion claims must reflect real, durable, verifiable behavior — never
  demo-only, in-memory-only, or mock-only. Mark temporary seams as transitional.
- Every active document is reachable from `docs/README.md`; update index and
  cross-links in the same change.
- Execution truth lives in `docs/plan/`. Re-earned progress is recorded in
  `docs/PROJECT-STATUS-RESET.md` and `docs/plan/execution-sync-ledger.md`.
- **Post-task doc sync is mandatory before Done** — see
  `.cursor/rules/post-task-doc-sync-constitution.mdc`.
- Prefer small, reviewable, diff-friendly documentation changes.
